1️⃣ If You Remove Helm From deploy.yaml, Who Renders the Templates?

In your architecture Helm is not used by the pipeline.

Helm is used by Argo CD internally.

Flow:

deploy.yaml
 |
kubectl apply application.yaml
 |
Argo CD Application created
 |
Argo CD repo-server clones Git repo
 |
Argo CD detects Helm chart
 |
Helm templates rendered
 |
Kubernetes manifests generated
 |
Deployment applied

So Helm runs inside Argo CD, not inside your pipeline.

Important point for interview:

Argo CD has built-in Helm support, so it can render Helm charts without Helm being installed in the pipeline.

2️⃣ What Happens When Helm Is Installed in infra.yaml?

In your infra pipeline you run:

helm upgrade --install argocd argo/argo-cd

This command:

1️⃣ Downloads the Argo CD Helm chart from the Helm repo
2️⃣ Helm renders the templates
3️⃣ Kubernetes resources are created

Helm chart for Argo CD contains many Kubernetes YAML templates.

Example:

argocd-server Deployment
argocd-repo-server Deployment
argocd-application-controller Deployment
argocd-dex-server Deployment
Services
ConfigMaps
RBAC roles

Helm processes those templates and sends them to Kubernetes.

Result:

Kubernetes cluster
 |
argocd namespace
 |
Argo CD components installed

So Helm was only used to install Argo CD.

After that Argo CD itself uses Helm to deploy your app.

3️⃣ Where Do the Helm Templates Come From?

They come from your repo:

helm/gitops-app
 |
Chart.yaml
values.yaml
templates/
 |
deployment.yaml
service.yaml
ingress.yaml

Inside templates/ you wrote files like:

deployment.yaml
service.yaml
ingress.yaml

These contain Helm template syntax:

{{ .Values.replicaCount }}
{{ .Values.service.port }}

Helm replaces these values using values.yaml.

Example:

Template:

replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }}

values.yaml:

replicaCount: 2

Rendered output:

replicas: 2

Then Argo CD applies the final Kubernetes YAML.

4️⃣ What Chart.yaml Actually Does

Chart.yaml is the metadata file for a Helm chart.

Example:

apiVersion: v2
name: gitops-app
version: 0.1.0
appVersion: "1.0"

Purpose:

Field	Meaning
apiVersion	Helm chart format
name	chart name
version	chart version
appVersion	application version

Helm uses this file to understand:

This folder is a Helm chart

Without Chart.yaml, Helm cannot load the chart.

So Chart.yaml is basically:

metadata + identification for the chart
5️⃣ How Argo CD Uses Helm

When Argo CD reads this in application.yaml:

source:
  path: helm/gitops-app

Argo CD does internally:

git clone repo
 |
detect Helm chart
 |
helm template helm/gitops-app
 |
generate Kubernetes YAML
 |
apply manifests

So Helm runs inside Argo CD repo-server.

